18. There was one Eutrapelus, who when he would do his enemies the
greateſt miſchief, made them rich, uſing to ſay, he thus took revenge on them;
for they were like to receive with their Riches a great burden of cares.

9. Mor. The moſt of us are ſlothfull in other mens buſineſs: but,
if thou would'ſt have any thing well looked to, put it not over to another,
but look to it thy ſelf.

22. Mor. This fable teacheth us that more pity is ſometimes found in
the brute creatures, than in thoſe men, that, beſides wealth, have no worth;
beſides ſhape, nothing of a man.

2. Mor. This fable belongs to them who are not content with their condition;
who, if they did but conſider other mens miſfortunes, would
more patiently endure their own.

