1. A Widow loathing a ſingle kind of life, had a mind to marry;
but ſhe durſt not, being afraid of the jeering of the common ſort,
which uſe to rail upon them that marry twice.

2. And being asked by the Bear, what the Aſses idleneſs, or the Hares
fearfulneſs, (whom he ſaw to he there amongſt other ſouldiers) could
avail him towards the victory, he anſwered;

1. THE Fox and the Libard wrangled about their fairneſs; and as
the Libard highly commended his own changeable coloured
skin, when the Fox could not more ſet out her own, ſhe ſaid;

2. Now the Bear coming to him, ſmelt at his ears and the hinder part
of his head, whilſt he that lay all along, held his breath continually;
ſo the Bear thinking that he was dead, went his way.

4. For, when a great wind came, the Reed was toſſed, and bent backward;
